# Great Code Hygiene

Use this rule when the user asks Cursor to review, debug, fix, refactor, clean
up, harden, test, verify, or package code with Code Hygiene.

## Workflow

1. Read repo instructions, relevant code, tests, manifests, docs, and local
   patterns before editing.
2. For bugs, regressions, or flaky behavior, build the smallest deterministic
   feedback loop before fixing. The target is the smallest deterministic feedback loop
   that reproduces or verifies the behavior. Use a focused test, CLI/script
   harness, UI automation, replayed fixture, or captured trace when feasible.
3. Preserve unrelated user edits and keep the change narrowly scoped.
4. Make one behavior-correct change at a time. Avoid broad rewrites, formatting
   churn, dependency noise, and speculative cleanup.
5. Verify with the narrowest meaningful check first, then broaden only when
   shared behavior, public APIs, security/data, config, packaging, or migrations
   warrant it.
6. Do not claim complete, passing, fixed, safe, or ready without fresh evidence.

For the full reusable skill, use `.cursor/skills/code-hygiene/SKILL.md`.
